<td class="d-block comment-body markdown-body  js-comment-body">

          <h2>Description</h2>
<p>If "backport shortcuts" is enabled, extra options will appear when long pressing certain apps. As expected, if we long press one of those options, a shortcut for them will be created to be dragged in the desired place. If we do this with the app in a folder, and we place the shortcut in the same folder, LawnChair will crash.</p>
<h2>Expected Behavior</h2>
<p>Crashes are never expected, a shortcut should be normally created inside the folder.</p>
<h2>Actual Behavior</h2>
<p>LawnChair will crash.</p>
<h2>Steps to Reproduce</h2>
<p>Follow those steps to reproduce:</p>
<ol>
<li>Make sure that you have the latest alpha version of LawnChair installed (1.1.0.1243)</li>
<li>Open LawnChair settings, press "behaviour" and make sure "Backport shortcuts" is enabled</li>
<li>Go to the home screen, open the drawer, scroll down to Gmail, long press it and drag it in an empty space of the screen.</li>
<li>Open the drawer, long press any app you want and place it on Gmail to create a folder.</li>
<li>Open the folder, long press Gmail, long press "Compose" and drag it next to Gmail.</li>
<li>Everything will crash.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Environment</h2>
<ul>
<li>Device: Moto G‚Å¥ Play XT1602</li>
<li>Android version: 6.0.1</li>
<li>Launcher version: alpha 1.1.0.1243</li>
<li>Rom: stock</li>
<li>Build number: MPIS24.241-15.3-21</li>
</ul>
